Porcupines don't have much to say. That's because they spend a lot of their time alone. They "talk" a bit when they're looking for mates and caring for their young. Sometimes they warn enemies___such as fishers, mountain lions, wolves, and people___to leave them alone. Porcupine warnings come in three forms___sight, sound, nd smell. The sharp difference between the light and dark hair on an adult's back and tail makes it easy to spot at night. If an enemy appears, the porcupine turns its back and uses its body like a flag.
